{
  "texts": [
    "Therefore, they require manual teleoperation [20] or external velocity planner to perform navigation [18].To address the above limitations of relying on embodimentspecific modules and the lack of velocity planning, X-Nav provides an end-to-end navigation approach that directly maps robot observations to executable low-level commands.",
    "This is achieved through a novel two-stage training framework, where multiple expert policies are trained on randomly generated robots, and distilled into a general navigation policy.",
    "The cross-embodiment navigation problem requires learning a single policy 𝜋!",
    "that enables an unseen mobile robot 𝓇 ∈ ℛ \"#$$% ∪ ℛ &'() to navigate from a starting position 𝑙 * ∈ ℝ + to a given goal position 𝑙, ∈ ℝ + at a reference speed 𝑣 ref ∈ ℝ in an unknown cluttered environment.",
    "The robot navigation is guided by: 1) the visual observations which are represented by depth images 𝑜)$-.# ∈ ℝ /×1 from an onboard depth camera, We consider both wheeled and quadruped robots."
  ]
}